# Fix Git Not Recognized Issue

The user is unable to run `git` commands because Git was extracted as a portable version and not added to the system PATH. This plan details how to permanently add Git to the system PATH and verify the fix.

## User Review Required

> [!IMPORTANT]
> I will be updating your user-level PATH environment variable to include the location of the Git executable. This will make the `git` command available in any new terminal window you open.

## Proposed Changes

I will use PowerShell to add `C:\Users\Mohammed\Downloads\PortableGit\cmd` to the User PATH environment variable.

### Environment Configuration

- **Target Path**: `C:\Users\Mohammed\Downloads\PortableGit\cmd`
- **Variable**: User PATH

## Verification Plan

### Automated Verification
- Run `git --version` in a new PowerShell session within my environment to confirm the change (though I may need to refresh the current session's path).
- Check the value of the PATH variable in the registry or via environment variable commands.

### Manual Verification
- I will ask you to open a **NEW** Command Prompt or PowerShell window and type `git --version` to verify it works for you.
